Let $P,$ $Q,$ and $R$ be represented in the complex plane, so by rewriting the complex numbers we have</think> 
\begin{align*}
P &= (x, y) \\
Q &= (x, y)(1+i) = (x-y, x+y) \\
R &= (2x, 2y) \\
\\ 
\text{By plotting} \hspace{0.5mm} P,& Q, \hspace{0.5mm} \text{and} \hspace{0.5mm} R \hspace{0.5mm} \text{on the cartesian plane, we can get that} \hspace{0.5mm} RS \parallel y=&-x \hspace{0.5mm} \text{and} \hspace{0.5mm} PS \parallel Q \text{and intersects the unit circle.}
\end{align*}
<answer>We can plot $P,$ $Q,$ and $R$ on complex plane, and obtain $P=(x,y), Q=ix-y+x+iy, and R=2x+2iy.$ Now, since $|z|=1,$ we know that $SSR\parallel iy+y=i(-x-x)+y=y,$ and thus since the $S$ is equidistant to $P,$ $Q,$ and $R,$ we can draw a circle by plotting $Q'=iP$ and $R'=-iR$ on the plane that would intersect the unit circle. Now, by Vieta's Formulas, $SS'=\sqrt{|Q-R|},$ where $S$ is one root of the equation $z^2+i(-x-x)+y=y,$ and so $|SS'|\leq |Summary \hspace{0.5mm} of \hspace{0.5mm} This \hspace{0.5mm} equation|=|Q'-R|=\sqrt{(-2x)^2+(2y)^2}=\sqrt{4+8y^2-8x^2+4x^4}=2 \sqrt{5}.$</answer>

problem:
A circle centered at $O$ has radius 1 and contains the point $A$. Segment $AB$ is tangent to the circle at $A$ and $\angle
AOB=\theta$. If point $C$ lies on $\overline{OA}$ and $\overline{BC}$ bisects $\angle ABO$, then express $OC$ in terms of $s$ and $c,$ where $s = \sin \theta$ and $c = \cos \theta.$

